    <fr:title text="Totally bounded">Totally bounded</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
    <fr:source-path>/Users/longie/forest/trees/FA-000O.tree</fr:source-path>
    <fr:date>
      <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
      <fr:month>5</fr:month>
      <fr:day>26</fr:day>
    </fr:date>
    <fr:authors>
      <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
    </fr:authors>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>A subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> of a metric space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X,d)]]></fr:tex> is said to be totally bounded if for every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ε > 0]]></fr:tex>, there exists a finite cover of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> by balls of radius <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ε]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
    <fr:p>In other words, for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ε > 0]]></fr:tex>, there exist finitely many points <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_1, x_2, \ldots , x_n \in  X]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S \subseteq  \cup _{i=1}^n B(x_i, ε)]]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B(x_i, ε)]]></fr:tex> is the ball with center <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_i]]></fr:tex> and radius <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ε]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
    <fr:p>In a complete metric space, a set is compact if and only if it is totally bounded and closed.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
