            <fr:title text="Compact">Compact</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:source-path>/Users/longie/forest/trees/FA-000H.tree</fr:source-path>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> of a topological space is said to be compact if every open cover of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> has a finite subcover.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>In metric spaces, compactness is equivalent to being <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000M.xml" addr="FA-000M" title="Sequentially compact">sequentially compact</fr:link> (every sequence has a convergent subsequence) and <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000N.xml" addr="FA-000N" title="Complete">complete</fr:link> and <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000O.xml" addr="FA-000O" title="Totally bounded">totally bounded</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>In <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex>, a set is compact if and only if it is closed and bounded (the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000P.xml" addr="FA-000P" title="Heine-Borel Theorem">Heine-Borel Theorem</fr:link>).</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
